          "body": "The chapter's closing verse (1:11) names three eschatological realities. **Reunification**: the divided kingdoms (split since 931 BC, 1 Kings 12) will be gathered together — undoing the most painful political wound in Israel's history. **One leader** (*rosh echad*, literally *one head*): a single sovereign over the reunified people. New Testament writers and historic Reformed commentators identify this head as the Davidic Messiah, fulfilled in Christ as the one Shepherd over one flock (John 10:16; Ezekiel 34:23; 37:22-25). **The great day of Jezreel**: the same valley that announced judgment (1:5) now announces sowing — *Jezreel* literally means *God sows*. The judgment day becomes the planting day. Hosea 1 ends not where it began; the chapter's logic is judgment-into-mercy, exile-into-gathering, scattering-into-sowing — and the engine of every reversal is God's prior covenant with Abraham and His settled purpose to have a people called *sons of the living God*."
